  "prompt": "What are long term effects of hepatitis A?",
  "response": "Most people who contract hepatitis A recover completely without long-term complications. However, in rare cases, some potential long-term effects include:\n\n1. Rare Complications\n- Liver failure (extremely uncommon)\n- Prolonged or relapsing symptoms\n- Cholestatic hepatitis (inflammation that blocks bile flow)\n\n2. Potential Short-Term Effects That Can Persist\n- Fatigue\n- Joint pain\n- Weakness\n- Decreased appetite\n\n3. Vulnerable Populations at Higher Risk\n- Older adults\n- People with pre-existing liver conditions\n- Those with weakened immune systems\n\n4. Recovery and Prognosis\n- Most people fully recover within a few months\n- No chronic infection develops\n- Typically provides lifelong immunity after infection\n\n5. Prevention\n- Vaccination\n- Good hygiene practices\n- Proper sanitation\n- Safe food and water consumption\n\nGenerally, hepatitis A is considered an acute infection with minimal long-term consequences for most individuals. Complete recovery is the typical outcome, and most people experience no lasting health impacts.\n\nAlways consult a healthcare professional for personalized medical advice regarding hepatitis A.",
